<tr id="L70"><td><a href="#L70">70</a></td><td>MCCOY:  There's no reading. They're like waxworks figures.</td></tr>

<tr id="L71"><td><a href="#L71">71</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: The main door slams shut, and there's a man in an embroidered coat playing the harpsichord</td></tr>

<tr id="L72"><td><a href="#L72">72</a></td><td>TRELANE:  I must say, they make a perfectly exquisite display pair, but I suppose you want them back now.</td></tr>

<tr id="L73"><td><a href="#L73">73</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: He waves his hand and the two men come back to life</td></tr>

<tr id="L74"><td><a href="#L74">74</a></td><td>SULU:  Where are we?</td></tr>

<tr id="L75"><td><a href="#L75">75</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Welcome to an island of peace on my stormy little planet of Gothos.</td></tr>

<tr id="L76"><td><a href="#L76">76</a></td><td>KIRK:  What happened? Fill me in.</td></tr>

<tr id="L77"><td><a href="#L77">77</a></td><td>MCCOY:  You disappeared from the bridge after Sulu. We've been looking for you for four hours.</td></tr>

<tr id="L78"><td><a href="#L78">78</a></td><td>TRELANE:  You must excuse my whimsical way of fetching you here, but when I saw you passing by I simply could not resist.</td></tr>

<tr id="L79"><td><a href="#L79">79</a></td><td>KIRK:  I'm Captain James Kirk of the United Starship Enterprise.</td></tr>

<tr id="L80"><td><a href="#L80">80</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Ah, so you're the Captain of these brave lads. My greetings and felicitations, Captain. So good of you and your officers to drop in. Absolutely smashing.</td></tr>

<tr id="L81"><td><a href="#L81">81</a></td><td>KIRK:  Who are you? Where do you come from?</td></tr>

<tr id="L82"><td><a href="#L82">82</a></td><td>SOMEONE: General Trelane, retired. At your service, sirs. My home is your home.</td></tr>

<tr id="L83"><td><a href="#L83">83</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: He goes back to his playing</td></tr>

<tr id="L84"><td><a href="#L84">84</a></td><td>DESALLE:  We've lost contact with the ship, Captain. We're trapped here.</td></tr>

<tr id="L85"><td><a href="#L85">85</a></td><td>TRELANE:  I can't tell you how delighted I am to have visitors from the very planet that I've made my hobby. Yes, but according to my observations, I didn't think you capable of such voyages.</td></tr>

<tr id="L86"><td><a href="#L86">86</a></td><td>JAEGER:  Notice the period, Captain. Nine hundred light years from Earth. It's what might be seen through a viewing scope if it were powerful enough.</td></tr>

<tr id="L87"><td><a href="#L87">87</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Ah, yes. I've been looking in on the doings on your lively little Earth.</td></tr>

<tr id="L88"><td><a href="#L88">88</a></td><td>KIRK:  Then you've been looking in on the doings nine hundred years past.</td></tr>

<tr id="L89"><td><a href="#L89">89</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Oh, really? Have I made an error in time? How fallible of me. Oh, I did so want to make you feel at home. I'm quite proud of the detail.</td></tr>

<tr id="L90"><td><a href="#L90">90</a></td><td>KIRK:  General Trelane.</td></tr>

<tr id="L91"><td><a href="#L91">91</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Retired, sir. Just Squire Trelane now. And you may call me Squire. Yes, I rather fancy that.</td></tr>

<tr id="L92"><td><a href="#L92">92</a></td><td>KIRK:  For what purpose have you imprisoned us here?</td></tr>

<tr id="L93"><td><a href="#L93">93</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Imprisoned? Nonsense. You're my guests. You see, I just finished my studies of your curious and fascinating society. You came by at the most propitious moment. I want to know all about your campaigns, your battles, your missions of conquest.</td></tr>

<tr id="L94"><td><a href="#L94">94</a></td><td>KIRK:  Our missions are peaceful, not for conquest. When we do battle, it is only because we have no choice.</td></tr>

<tr id="L95"><td><a href="#L95">95</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Ah, but that's the official story, eh?</td></tr>

<tr id="L96"><td><a href="#L96">96</a></td><td>KIRK:  I must ask you to let us go back to our ship.</td></tr>

<tr id="L97"><td><a href="#L97">97</a></td><td>TRELANE:  I wouldn't hear of it. You shall join me in a repast. I want to learn all about your feelings on war and killing and conquest. That sort of thing. Do you know that you're one of the few predator species that preys even on itself?</td></tr>

<tr id="L98"><td><a href="#L98">98</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Kirk returns to the main group, where DeSalle has his hand on his phaser</td></tr>

<tr id="L99"><td><a href="#L99">99</a></td><td>KIRK:  Not yet. Put it on stun, not to kill, DeSalle.</td></tr>

<tr id="L100"><td><a href="#L100">100</a></td><td>TRELANE:  DeSalle, did you say? Un vrai Francais?</td></tr>

<tr id="L101"><td><a href="#L101">101</a></td><td>DESALLE:  My ancestry is French, yes.</td></tr>

<tr id="L102"><td><a href="#L102">102</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Ah, monsieur. Vive la gloire. Vive Napoleon. You know, I admire your Napoleon very much.</td></tr>

<tr id="L103"><td><a href="#L103">103</a></td><td>KIRK:  This is Mister DeSalle, our navigator. Doctor McCoy, our medical officer. Mister Sulu, our helmsman, and Carl Jaeger, meteorologist.</td></tr>

<tr id="L104"><td><a href="#L104">104</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Welcome, good physicianer and honourable sir. (bows low)</td></tr>

<tr id="L105"><td><a href="#L105">105</a></td><td>SULU:  Is he kidding?</td></tr>

<tr id="L106"><td><a href="#L106">106</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Und Offizier Jaeger, und der deutsche Soldat, nein? (gives a little Prussian salute then marches around) Eins, zwei, drei, vier. Gehen vir mit dem Schiessgewehr.</td></tr>

<tr id="L107"><td><a href="#L107">107</a></td><td>JAEGER:  I'm a scientist, not a military man.</td></tr>

<tr id="L108"><td><a href="#L108">108</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Oh come now. We're all military men under the skin. And how we do love our uniforms.</td></tr>

<tr id="L109"><td><a href="#L109">109</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Trelane is admiring himself in his mirror when he spots DeSalle raising his weapon, and with a wave of the hand, stops him</td></tr>

<tr id="L110"><td><a href="#L110">110</a></td><td>TRELANE:  What an interesting weapon you've got there. Do let me see it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L111"><td><a href="#L111">111</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: He takes it out of DeSalle's hand, and he can move again</td></tr>

<tr id="L112"><td><a href="#L112">112</a></td><td>TRELANE: : Yes. Now let me see. How does this work? Ah, yes. This won't kill, and this will.</td></tr>

<tr id="L113"><td><a href="#L113">113</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: He fires it at the Salt Monster, who is disintegrated</td></tr>

<tr id="L114"><td><a href="#L114">114</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Oh, how marvellous! (destroys another exhibit) Devastating! Why, this could kill millions.</td></tr>

<tr id="L115"><td><a href="#L115">115</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Kirk takes it off him</td></tr>

<tr id="L116"><td><a href="#L116">116</a></td><td>KIRK:  Who will you start with, my crew? Are we your next targets?</td></tr>

<tr id="L117"><td><a href="#L117">117</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Oh, how absolutely typical of your species. You don't understand something, so you become fearful. Now, do let me anticipate your next question. You want to know how I've managed all of this.</td></tr>

<tr id="L118"><td><a href="#L118">118</a></td><td>KIRK:  That's correct.</td></tr>

<tr id="L119"><td><a href="#L119">119</a></td><td>TRELANE:  We, meaning I and others, have, to state the matter briefly, perfected a system by which matter can be transferred to energy and back to matter again.</td></tr>

<tr id="L120"><td><a href="#L120">120</a></td><td>KIRK:  Like the transporter system aboard the Enterprise.</td></tr>

<tr id="L121"><td><a href="#L121">121</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Oh, a crude example of an infinitely more sophisticated process. You see, we not only transport matter from place to place, but we can alter its shape at will.</td></tr>

<tr id="L122"><td><a href="#L122">122</a></td><td>KIRK:  This drawing room, did you create it by rearranging matter on this planet?</td></tr>

<tr id="L123"><td><a href="#L123">123</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Quite.</td></tr>

<tr id="L124"><td><a href="#L124">124</a></td><td>KIRK:  I see. How did you manage</td></tr>

<tr id="L125"><td><a href="#L125">125</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Dear Captain, your inquiries are becoming tiresome. I want you to be happy. Free yourself of care. Let's enjoy ourselves in the spirit of martial good fellowship.</td></tr>

<tr id="L126"><td><a href="#L126">126</a></td><td>KIRK:  Come on, let's go. We're getting out of here.</td></tr>

<tr id="L127"><td><a href="#L127">127</a></td><td>TRELANE:  Tut, tut, tut. You're being quite rude. You can't go. Apparently, you need another demonstration of my authority. Yes, quite.</td></tr>

<tr id="L128"><td><a href="#L128">128</a></td><td>SOMEONE: (Kirk vanishes from the room and is in the natural atmosphere of the planet, choking on the fumes. Everyone in the room can hear him. Trelane brings him back) Now, that's a sample of the atmosphere of this planet outside my kindly influence. Now, you will behave yourself hereafter, won't you? Or I shall be very, very angry.</td></tr>

<tr id="L129"><td><a href="#L129">129</a></td><td>SOMEONE: Captain's Log Stardate 2125.7. Science Officer Spock reporting for Captain Kirk. We have completed fourteenth orbit of this planet without establishing contact with our missing officers or the parties sent to find them. Subspace communications remain blocked. However, by diverting impulse power to our sensors, we have made them operable, and we have detected one small area on the surface which seems relatively stable.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Bridge</td></tr>
<tr id="L130"><td><a href="#L130">130</a></td><td>SCOTT:  Aye, it's there, Mister Spock. Peaceful as Earth, but how do you explain it?</td></tr>

<tr id="L131"><td><a href="#L131">131</a></td><td>SPOCK:  I don't, Mister Scott. It simply exists. Artificial perhaps, or a freak of nature. The fact remains that life can exist in that area.</td></tr>

<tr id="L132"><td><a href="#L132">132</a></td><td>SCOTT:  Aye, it could, but it couldn't move around much.</td></tr>

<tr id="L133"><td><a href="#L133">133</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Apply a fine tuning on our sensors. Locate any life forms in that stable area.</td></tr>

<tr id="L134"><td><a href="#L134">134</a></td><td>SCOTT:  If we find any, it doesn't follow that it would be our people.</td></tr>

<tr id="L135"><td><a href="#L135">135</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Affirmative. But if the Captain is down there and alive, that's where he'll have to be. We'll attempt to transport up any living beings our sensors detect.</td></tr>

<tr id="L136"><td><a href="#L136">136</a></td><td>SCOTT:  Shooting in the dark, Mister Spock?</td></tr>

<tr id="L137"><td><a href="#L137">137</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Or stand by and do nothing, Mister Scott.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Drawing Room</td></tr>
<tr id="L138"><td><a href="#L138">138</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Trelane is showing off his decor</td></tr>

<tr id="L139"><td><a href="#L139">139</a></td><td>SOMEONE: And this, of course, is an array of your battle flags and pennants dating back to the Crusades, to Hannibal's invaders, the Grecian war galleys, and the hordes of Persia. Can't you imagine it, Captain? The thousands of men marching off to their deaths, singing beneath these banners. Doesn't it make your blood run swiftly?</td></tr>

<tr id="L140"><td><a href="#L140">140</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Then he goes back to his music</td></tr>

<tr id="L141"><td><a href="#L141">141</a></td><td>SULU:  Captain, where could he possibly come from? Who is this maniac?</td></tr>

<tr id="L142"><td><a href="#L142">142</a></td><td>MCCOY:  Better say, what is he? I monitored him, and what I found was unbelievable.</td></tr>

<tr id="L143"><td><a href="#L143">143</a></td><td>KIRK:  Not alive?</td></tr>

<tr id="L144"><td><a href="#L144">144</a></td><td>MCCOY:  Not in the way we define life. No trace. Zero.</td></tr>

<tr id="L145"><td><a href="#L145">145</a></td><td>SULU:  You mean, it shows he's dead?</td></tr>

<tr id="L146"><td><a href="#L146">146</a></td><td>MCCOY:  It doesn't even show that he exists at all, alive or dead.</td></tr>

